<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-645-379  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 645 379.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  Dec 3 1990 v12 n49 p5(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>OS/2 acceptance is hampered as Windows soars. (Forrester ResearchInc. figures)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Scannell, Ed.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Sales figure predictions from Forrester Research Inc indicate thatthe success of Microsoft Windows is impeding acceptance of OS/2.andO;Forrester predicts that 915,000 copies of OS/2 will be sold in1994, in contrast with its January 1990 prediction of 3.3 millioncopies.andP;  The research firm expects Microsoft Corp to ship slightlymore than 4 million copies of Windows in the US in 1994.andP;  and 1.4million copies in 1990.andP;  Windows' big sales are expected tocontinue due to future enhancements, its growing acceptance inclient/server computing and the availability of applications fromlarge software vendors.andP;  However, both IBM and Microsoft officialscontend that OS/2 still plays an important role in their long-termplans.andP;  They argue that although Windows is an importantbreakthrough, it is not a replacement for OS/2 because OS/2 offerssuperior multitasking capabilities.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Forrester Research Inc. (Research)International Business Machines Corp. (Products)Microsoft Corp. (Products).andO;Ticker:    MSFT; IBM.andO;Product:   Microsoft Windows (Graphical user interface) (Sales statistics).andO;Topic:     OS-2SalesCompetitionOperating SystemsMarket Analysis.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>